SERVICE

>> Service is a method for exposing a network application that is running as one or more Pods in your cluster.

>> You use a Service to make that set of Pods available on the network so that clients can interact with it.

>> The Service API, part of Kubernetes, is an abstraction to help you expose groups of Pods over a network. 

>>Each Service object defines a logical set of endpoints (usually these endpoints are Pods) along with a policy about how to make those pods accessible.

WHY SERVICES EXIST

> Problem with Pods
Pods are ephemeral (they die and get recreated)
Pod IPs keep changing
So, you cannot rely on Pod IP to access your app

>> Service provides:
1. Stable IP/DNS name
2. Load balancing across Pods

User → Service → Pods

Service acts as a stable entry point

HOW SERVICE WORKS INTERNALLY?

> uses labels and selectors
> Routes traffic to matching pods
selector:
  app: nginx
> any pod with label app=nginx will recieve traffic

>> A Service is defined using YAML or JSON, like all Kubernetes object manifests. The set of Pods targeted by a Service is usually determined by a label selector 

>> Although each Pod has a unique IP address, those IPs are not exposed outside the cluster without a Service. Services allow your applications to receive traffic.

CLUSTER IP

>> Exposes Service inside the cluster only
>> Exposes the Service on an internal IP in the cluster. This type makes the Service only reachable from within the cluster.

> Key Features
Internal communication only
Not accessible from outside
Default service type

YAML FILE 

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: nginx-clusterip
spec:
  type: ClusterIP
  selector:
    app: nginx
  ports:
  - port: 80
    targetPort: 80

Pod A → Service (ClusterIP) → Pod B

used cases : backend APIs , DB communications and microservices communication


NODEPORT 

>> Exposes Services on a port of every Node
>> Exposes the service on the same port of each selected node in the cluster using NAT. Makes a Service accessible from outside the cluster using NodeIP:NodePort. Superset of ClusterIP

>> Accessible from outside cluster
>> Opens a port (30000-32767) on all nodes

YAML FILE

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: nginx-nodeport
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: nginx
  ports:
   - port: 80
     targetPort: 80
     nodePort: 300007

User → NodeIP:NodePort → Service → Pod
http://<NodeIP>:30007

>> Works even if pod is on another node
>> K8S routes traffic internally

LOADBALANCER

>> Creates an external Load balancer in the current cloud(if supported) and assigns a fixed, external IP to the service. Superset of NodePort

>> Exposes Service using a cloud provider's external load balancer

>> Public IP
>> Automatically provisions load balancer
>> Best for production

YAML FILE

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: nginx-lb
spec:
  type: LoadBalancer
  selector:
    app: nginx
  ports:
   - port: 80
     targrtPort: 80

User → External Load Balancer → Node → Pod

Cloud creates:
External IP
Load balancer
Traffic distributed across nodes

Feature	      ClusterIP	      NodePort	         LoadBalancer
Access	      Internal	  External via Node	    External via LB
Default	         Yes	          No	              No
Security	   High	           Medium	             High
Use case	Internal services	Testing	           Production

>> targetPort vs port vs nodePort
ports:
- port: 80
  targetPort: 8080
  nodePort: 30007

targetPort → container port
port → service port
nodePort → external port

>> kube-proxy : Handles Routing traffic to Pods Load balancing

SCENARIOS

1. Service not working
>> causes : selector mismatch, No pods running
>> Debug 
kubectl get pods --show-labels
kubectl describe svc <service>

2. No Endpoints
kubectl get endpoints
>> if empty, service not linked to pods

3. Traffic not reaching Pod
>> causes : wrong targetPort, App not listening on port
# 1. Check Pods
kubectl get pods
# 2. Check Service
kubectl get svc
# 3. Check Endpoints
kubectl get endpoints
# 4. Check logs
kubectl logs <pod>
# 5. Test inside Pod
kubectl exec -it <pod> -- curl localhost:<port>

4. LoadBalancer not getting IP
This usually happens when running Kubernetes on local or bare-metal environments without cloud integration. Since LoadBalancer relies on cloud providers, the external IP remains pending. Solutions include using NodePort, minikube tunnel, or MetalLB.


A Service = stable entry point + load balancer for Pods
ClusterIP : Only apps inside the cluster can talk to it
NodePort: Expose app using Node’s IP and a port
LoadBalancer: Cloud gives you a public IP and handles everything

ClusterIP → internal only  
NodePort → manual external access  
LoadBalancer → production-ready external access  

Inside cluster → ClusterIP
Local testing → NodePort
Production → LoadBalancer + Ingress

ClusterIP is used for internal communication within the cluster, NodePort exposes the service via a node’s IP and port for external access, and LoadBalancer provides a cloud-managed external IP with automatic traffic distribution, making it suitable for production.